-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 12: evaluate format-spec (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { format-spec }
-- Final output cell.

⊢ format-spec
  given collect-requirements→all-requirements ≡ ["R-E1...", ..., "R-I9e..."]
  given request→text ≡ "Build me a chat app"
  yield specification

-- LLM evaluation (simulated):

  yield specification ≡ "
# Requirements Specification: Chat Application
## Original Request: 'Build me a chat app'

## 1. Functional Requirements

### 1.1 Core (Explicit)
  1. [EXPLICIT] R-E1: The system is a software application.
  2. [EXPLICIT] R-E2: The application supports chat — sending and receiving text messages between two or more parties.
  3. [EXPLICIT] R-E3: The application is built from scratch.
  4. [EXPLICIT] R-E4: The requester is the owner/stakeholder.

### 1.2 Identity (Implicit)
  5. [IMPLICIT-certain] R-I1: Users must create accounts to identify themselves.

### 1.3 Messaging (Implicit)
  6. [IMPLICIT-certain] R-I2: Messages are persisted — viewable after app restart.
  7. [IMPLICIT-certain] R-I3a: Message delivery within 2s on broadband (≥5 Mbps).
  8. [IMPLICIT-certain] R-I3b: Message delivery within 5s on 3G (≥1 Mbps).
  9. [IMPLICIT-certain] R-I3c: Typing indicators appear within 1s.

### 1.4 Presence (Implicit)
  10. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I6a: 'Online' status when active within last 5 minutes.
  11. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I6b: 'Away' status when inactive 5-30 minutes.
  12. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I6c: 'Offline' status when inactive >30 min or app closed.
  13. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I6d: Presence updates propagate within 10 seconds.

### 1.5 Notifications (Implicit)
  14. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I8a: Push notifications when app tab not in focus.
  15. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I8b: Notifications show sender name + first 50 characters.
  16. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I8c: Per-conversation mute control available.
  17. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I8d: Muted conversations do not trigger notifications.
  18. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I8e: Notification delivery within 5s of message send.

## 2. Non-Functional Requirements

### 2.1 Performance (Implicit)
  19. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I5a: Initial app load within 3 seconds on broadband.
  20. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I5b: Conversation switching < 500ms.
  21. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I5c: 60fps scrolling with up to 10,000 messages.
  22. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I5d: Search returns results within 2s for 100k messages.

### 2.2 Reliability (Implicit)
  23. [IMPLICIT-possible] R-I9a: 'Offline' banner appears within 3s of disconnection.
  24. [IMPLICIT-possible] R-I9b: Messages queued offline, sent on reconnection.
  25. [IMPLICIT-possible] R-I9c: Auto-reconnect every 5s, exponential backoff to 60s.
  26. [IMPLICIT-possible] R-I9d: Missed messages fetched in chronological order.
  27. [IMPLICIT-possible] R-I9e: No data loss for disconnections up to 24 hours.

### 2.3 Compatibility (Implicit)
  28. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I7a: Responsive web app on Safari iOS 15+, Chrome Android 10+.
  29. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I7b: UI adapts to widths 320px-428px.
  30. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I7c: Touch targets ≥ 44×44 CSS pixels.
  31. [IMPLICIT-likely] R-I7d: Functions on cellular data ≥ 1 Mbps.

## 3. Security Requirements

### 3.1 Privacy (Implicit)
  32. [IMPLICIT-certain] R-I4: Conversations are private — only participants can access messages.

## Summary
  - Total requirements: 32
  - Explicit: 4 (12.5%)
  - Implicit: 28 (87.5%)
    - Certain: 7
    - Likely: 16
    - Possible: 5
  - Concreteness: 100% (all requirements are testable)
"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ specification groups requirements by category → ✓ (Functional, Non-Functional, Security)
--   ⊨ specification numbers each requirement → ✓ (1-32)
--   ⊨ specification marks each as explicit or implicit → ✓ ([EXPLICIT], [IMPLICIT-*])
--   ⊨ every requirement from all-requirements appears → ✓ (32/32)

-- state after frame 12: format-spec frozen.
-- No more ready cells. Program quiescent.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- EXECUTION SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Total frames: 13 (0-12)
-- ⊢∘ iterations: 1 (converged immediately — all decompositions concrete)
-- Cells evaluated: request, extract-explicit, extract-implicit,
--   assess-concreteness, spawn-decomposers, decomposer-0..5 (6 cells),
--   collect-requirements, format-spec
--
-- Input: 5 words ("Build me a chat app")
-- Output: 32 testable requirements across 4 categories
-- Amplification factor: 6.4 requirements per input word
--
-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: vague requests are mostly implicit requirements
--   Of 32 final requirements, only 4 (12.5%) were explicit. The remaining
--   87.5% were implicit — unstated expectations from domain convention.
--   This quantifies the "curse of knowledge" in software requirements:
--   requesters assume shared context that doesn't exist.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: ⊢⊢ spawner enables embarrassingly parallel decomposition
--   All 6 decomposer cells are independent — they share no inputs except
--   the template. In a parallel runtime, frames 5-10 execute simultaneously.
--   Decomposition parallelism scales linearly with the number of vague
--   requirements: O(N) cells for N vague items.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: recursive depth controlled by semantic judgment is safe
--   The decompose-template marks all-concrete = true/false based on LLM
--   judgment. In this trace, all decompositions succeeded in one pass
--   (depth 1). The ⊢∘ loop WOULD recurse if any decomposer returned
--   all-concrete = false, spawning second-level decomposers. The max=3
--   bound on ⊢∘ prevents infinite recursion regardless of LLM judgment.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: confidence classification enables prioritization
--   The certain/likely/possible classification from extract-implicit creates
--   a natural priority ordering: build 'certain' requirements first, then
--   'likely', and treat 'possible' as stretch goals. This maps directly
--   to MVP → V1 → V2 product planning without additional analysis.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: the concreteness oracle is self-bootstrapping
--   The concreteness assessment (frame 3) is itself a soft cell — an LLM
--   judges whether requirements are testable. But the decomposition step
--   forces concreteness by requiring measurable criteria (oracle on
--   decompose-template). The system bootstraps from vague judgment to
--   concrete specification through oracle pressure, not through better
--   initial judgment. This is Cell's core pattern: oracles drive quality.
